<validation>
1. Demonstrate authentication bypass or account enumeration.
2. Show authorization policy circumvention.
3. Prove mass assignment modifying unauthorized properties.
4. Document SQL injection through EF Core.
5. Provide evidence of XSS through Razor rendering.
</validation>

<false_positives>
- [Authorize] consistently applied
- Anti-forgery validation on all state-changing endpoints
- ViewModels/DTOs preventing mass assignment
- EF Core using parameterized queries only
- Razor auto-encoding not bypassed
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Authentication bypass and account takeover
- Privilege escalation via authorization bypass
- Data manipulation through mass assignment
- Database compromise via SQL injection
- Session hijacking through XSS
- Information disclosure via configuration
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Check for [ApiController] - disables some protections.
2. FromSqlRaw is almost always vulnerable.
3. [AllowAnonymous] can override class-level [Authorize].
4. Model binding binds all public properties by default.
5. Html.Raw and JavaScript contexts are XSS vectors.
6. SignalR hubs may have different auth than controllers.
7. Anti-forgery tokens needed on all state-changing POSTs.
8. Developer exception page reveals stack traces.
9. Connection strings often in plain text config.
10. Check middleware order - security middleware must be early.
</pro_tips>

<remember>ASP.NET Core provides robust security features, but they must be correctly configured and applied. Mass assignment through model binding, raw SQL queries, and missing authorization attributes are common vulnerabilities. Always verify that security middleware is properly ordered and that attributes are consistently applied.</remember>
</aspnet_core_security_guide>
